identify the first quartile (Q1) and third quartile (Q3):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EQ1 is the median of the lower half of the data = 139.5\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EQ3 is the median of the upper half of the data = 143.5\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIQR = Q3 - Q1 = 143.5 - 139.5 = \u003Cstrong\u003E4 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe IQR is a useful measure of spread as it is not affected by extreme values and represents the middle 50% of the data. It can also be used to identify potential outliers, defined as values that fall more than 1.5 \u00d7 IQR below Q1 or above Q3.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The interquartile range (IQR) represents the middle 50% of a dataset, calculated as the difference between the 75th and 25th percentiles.","The IQR is a robust measure of spread that is not affected by extreme outliers.","The IQR can be used to identify outliers, defined as values more than 1.5 \u00d7 IQR below Q1 or above Q3."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55751"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55751"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T11:06:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T11:07:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70287"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd